🧠 OS Concept 1: Copy-on-Write (COW)
1️⃣ Simple Idea

When a process is copied (like using fork()),
👉 OS does NOT immediately copy memory

Instead:

👉 both processes share same memory (read-only)

Copy happens only when one tries to modify

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Photocopy book 📖

Instead of copying whole book:

👉 share same book
👉 copy only when someone writes on it

⚙️ Why It Works

Most child processes after fork():

👉 immediately call exec()

So copying entire memory = waste ❌

COW saves:

✔ memory
✔ time

🔗 Connection

From Day 9:

fork() creates process
COW optimizes it
🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why Copy-on-Write is efficient?

👉 Because it avoids unnecessary copying.

🧠 Memory Trick
COW = copy only when writing
🧠 OS Concept 2: IPC (Inter-Process Communication)

Processes don’t share memory (unlike threads).

So they communicate via:

👉 IPC

🔹 Types of IPC
1️⃣ Pipes

Simple communication between related processes.

Process A → Process B
2️⃣ Message Queues

Send messages via OS-managed queue.

3️⃣ Shared Memory 🔥

Fastest IPC.

Both processes access same memory region.

🧠 Analogy

Pipes → talking through pipe
Queue → mailbox
Shared memory → shared whiteboard

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Which IPC is fastest?

👉 Shared memory

🧠 Memory Trick
Pipe = simple
Queue = structured
Shared = fastest
⚙️ COA Concept 3: Branch Prediction
1️⃣ Simple Idea

CPU guesses:

👉 which path program will take (if/else)

Why Needed?

Branch instructions cause:

👉 pipeline stalls

🧠 Example
if(x > 0)

CPU predicts:

👉 true or false

If correct:

✔ fast execution

If wrong:

❌ pipeline flushed (waste time)

🧠 Analogy

Predicting traffic route 🚗

Correct → smooth
Wrong → delay

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why branch prediction is used?

👉 To reduce pipeline stalls.

🧠 Memory Trick
Predict branch → save time
⚙️ COA Concept 4: Write Buffer
1️⃣ Simple Idea

When CPU writes data:

👉 it may not wait for memory

Instead:

👉 data goes to write buffer

Then later to memory.

Why Needed?

Memory is slow.

CPU should not wait.

🧠 Analogy

Write notes quickly in rough notebook,
update final copy later.

🔗 Connection

Works well with:

👉 write-back cache

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why write buffer improves performance?

👉 CPU doesn’t wait for memory writes.

🧠 Memory Trick
Buffer = temporary holding
